:"1189","1200":"1200","ABT    1140":"about 1140","1175":"1175","1140":"1140","AFT    1189":"after 1189","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carrow","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Caro  .","Altered form of French   Caron   or of its variant or altered form   Carron  . Compare   Corrow  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carow","meanings":["English: variant of   Carrow  .","Americanized form ofGerman   Karow  ."]},{"name":"Caro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Miguel, Jesus, Carlos, Luis, Francisco, Juan, Jaime, Manuel, Ramon, Ruben, Angel.","Spanish, Portuguese, Italian, and Jewish (Sephardic): nickname from Portuguese, Spanish, Italian <i>caro</i> ‘dear, beloved’ (from Latin <i>carus</i>). In medieval Italy this was also in use as a personal name. Compare   De Caro   and   Di Caro  .","Italian (Sicily; <b>Carò</b>): variant of <b>Carrò</b> (see   Carro  )."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Peter Carrow was born about 1140. He had at least 1 son. He died after 1189."},"et":{"ABT    1140–AFT    1189"